h3. Issue Summary
Content of a custom URL field is not showing in the "Jira issue/filter" macro 

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a Jira Software project;
# Create a custom URL field;
# Add information in this custom field;
# Create a Confluence page;
# Add the "Jira issue/filter" macro in this page;
# Create a query to search project where you added information to the custom URL field created;
# Open the *Display options* of the macro
# Add the custom URL field created in the *Columns to display*

h3. Expected Results
The macro will show the columns set in the search of your macro, and the proper information of those fields.

h3. Actual Results
The custom URL field is not populated.

h3. Workaround
There is no workaround at the moment.

h3. Issue Summary

we have found that blog posts are not currently supported by the "Single Copy Page" REST API or maybe we are doing it wrong.
h3. Steps to Reproduce

We have tried using the following endpoint: `host`/wiki/rest/api/content/`contentId`/copy
with this request JSON body:
{code:java}
{
 "copyAttachments": true,
 "copyPermissions": true,
 "copyProperties": true,
 "copyLabels": true,
 "copyCustomContents": true,
 "destination": {
 "type": "space",
 "value": "PS"
 }
}{code}
and this is the response we got:
{code:java}
{
 "statusCode": 404,
 "data": {
 "authorized": false,
 "valid": true,
 "errors": [],
 "successful": false
 },
 "message": "com.atlassian.confluence.api.service.exceptions.NotFoundException: Source page not found"
}{code}
h3. Expected Results

Blog post get copied to destination space with same date
h3. Actual Results

404 error as mentioned in the steps to reproduce field

 
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

According to our [API documentation|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/api-group-template/#api-api-template-post], in order to create a template, the payload for the template's body needs to be according below structure:
{code:java}
"body": {
    "value": "<string>",
    "representation": "view"
  }
{code}
However, using this structure won't work.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Follow the steps provided on our API documentation to create a template.

h3. Expected Results

The template should be created.
h3. Actual Results

The attempt will fail (400 error). For example:
{code:java}
{'statusCode': 400, 'data': {'authorized': False, 'valid': True, 'errors': [], 'successful': False}, 'message': 'com.atlassian.confluence.api.service.exceptions.BadRequestException: com.atlassian.confluence.api.service.exceptions.BadRequestException: Cannot find valid content for template from contentTemplate'} {code}
h3. Workaround

Use below structure for the body's payload:
{code:java}
"body": {
   "storage": {
      "value": "<string>",
      "representation": "view"
   }
} 
{code}

h3. Issue Summary

AP.content.getContext() returns an empty object in dynamic content macro editors.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create an app with a dynamic content macro defining a custom editor.
 # Open the editor and call AP.context.getContext(callback)

h3. Expected Results

The callback is called with a context object similar to:

 

 
{code:java}
confluence: {
  content: {
    id: "12345678"
    type: "page"
    version: "7"
  }
  macro: {
    hash: "58e722af-f259-41be-a8df-ddddddd"
    id: "58e722af-f259-41be-a8df-eeeeeeee"
  }
  space: {
    id: "1234567"
    key: "FOO"
  }
}
{code}
 
h3. Actual Results

The context object is empty (for an unlicensed app):
{noformat}
{}{noformat}
h3. Workaround

None

h3. Issue Summary

The *Filter Results* macro is amazing to pull up JIRA information on Confluence pages, making beautiful reports of our projects.
Though, when inserting a new Filter or editing an existing one, if you have a numbered field on your JIRA project and would like to add it into the filter, it won't work.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a custom field on JIRA (or select an existing custom one created by Jira, like Story points), selecting the Numbered one.
# Still on JIRA, create a filter from a project that you added the previously created custom field;
# Go to Confluence and create a new page;
# Call the widget with */filter*;
# Chose the filter you just created;
# On the add fields drop-down list, find the numbered custom field you created and add it;
# Save the display options of the widget.

h3. Expected Results
A preview of the widget is loaded.

h3. Actual Results
Nothing happens and you can no longer use this macro - you have to cancel and start it over.

*Notes*:
* As soon as you hit the *Save* option in the display options, some 200 requests are displayed, but with an error similar to this: {{SyntaxError: JSON.parse: unexpected keyword at line 1 column 1 of the JSON data}}
* The issue also happens when a user using  Text Field (multi-line) and Select List (single choice)

h3. Workaround

Users may use Jira issue macro to display the field.
